{
  "answer": "**Ghalib's ghazal \"Yeh na thi hamārī qismat ke visāl-e-yār hotā\" (Chapter 204 of *Diwan-e-Ghalib*) opens by lamenting that union with the beloved (*visāl-e-yār*, literally \"meeting\" or \"union with the friend/beloved\") was not the poet's destiny (*qismat*, fate).**[^1]\n\nThe first *sher* (couplet) states:\n\n> To be with my Beloved was not my fate;  \n> Had I lived longer, waiting was my state.[^2]\n\nThis expresses resignation: rather than fulfillment through meeting the beloved, the poet's lot was prolonged anticipation (*intezār*). The subsequent verses elaborate on unfulfilled promises, fragile vows, and the inevitability of sorrow, but the core idea about the beloved's inaccessibility is rooted in this fatalistic opening.[^3]\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch. 204 (\"Yeh na thi hamari qismat ke visaal-e-yaar hota\"), [translation](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/204-yeh-na-thi-hamari-qismat-ke-visaal-e-yaar-hota/translation/).\n\n[^2]: *Ibid.*, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/204-yeh-na-thi-hamari-qismat-ke-visaal-e-yaar-hota/translation/#p-e43078).\n\n[^3]: *Ibid.*, [paragraphs](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/204-yeh-na-thi-hamari-qismat-ke-visaal-e-yaar-hota/translation/#p-e43078#p-56a7ac).",
